<section class="layer" id="stack">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="sec-head sa">
            <span class="sec-label">THE ENCRYPTION STACK</span>
            <h2 class="sec-title">From <span class="grad-r">Alexa to Zigbee</span><br>every layer encrypted.</h2>
            <p class="sec-sub">Your smart home isn't one device — it's five layers of communication between your voice, your hub, and the bee-shaped chip in your light bulb. Here's what each layer does, what it speaks, and how we lock it down.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="stack sa">
            <!-- Layer 1: Voice -->
            <div class="stack-layer l1">
                <div class="layer-num">01</div>
                <div class="stack-name">
                    Voice & UI Layer
                    <span class="protocol">TLS 1.3</span>
                    <span class="protocol">HTTPS</span>
                </div>
                <p class="stack-desc">Voice commands ("turn off the porch light"), phone-app taps, dashboard clicks. With Big Tech, this audio rides up to Amazon or Google. With BDG, it lands on <strong style="color:var(--purple);">your private cloud</strong> — same TLS 1.3 encryption Banks use, just terminating on hardware you own.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="flow-down"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor"><path d="M12 4v16m0 0l-6-6m6 6l6-6" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/></svg></div>

            <!-- Layer 2: Edge cloud -->
            <div class="stack-layer l2">
                <div class="layer-num">02</div>
                <div class="stack-name">
                    BDG Private Edge Cloud
                    <span class="protocol">PI 5 + LINUX</span>
                    <span class="protocol">SUPABASE LOCAL</span>
                </div>
                <p class="stack-desc">A small Raspberry Pi 5 server, sitting on a shelf in your house. Runs the dashboard, the automation engine, and the data store. Encrypted file system. <strong style="color:var(--teal);">No internet required for local commands.</strong> Internet's only used when YOU explicitly want it — for remote access (WireGuard VPN) or backup.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="flow-down"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor"><path d="M12 4v16m0 0l-6-6m6 6l6-6" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/></svg></div>

            <!-- Layer 3: Hub-to-device protocols -->
            <div class="stack-layer l3">
                <div class="layer-num">03</div>
                <div class="stack-name">
                    Hub-to-Device Protocols
                    <span class="protocol">MATTER 1.3</span>
                    <span class="protocol">WPA3</span>
                </div>
                <p class="stack-desc">Your edge cloud talks to bigger devices (thermostats, cameras, hubs) over your Wi-Fi or Ethernet. We use Matter 1.3 (the new open smart-home standard) wherever supported, plus WPA3 on the network. Authentication is per-device — no shared credentials means one bad device can't compromise the others.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="flow-down"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor"><path d="M12 4v16m0 0l-6-6m6 6l6-6" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/></svg></div>

            <!-- Layer 4: Mesh -->
            <div class="stack-layer l4">
                <div class="layer-num">04</div>
                <div class="stack-name">
                    Mesh Radio (the Honey Bee layer 🐝)
                    <span class="protocol">ZIGBEE 3.0</span>
                    <span class="protocol">Z-WAVE</span>
                    <span class="protocol">THREAD</span>
